##New Corpulmonale patient: 13 days in hospital, how did I cure the discharge?

As a new mild coronary pneumonia patients, Lin Qi experienced 13 days of difficult waiting and treatment period, successfully cured home.

After discharge from the hospital, Lin Qi at home for a single isolation. She shared her treatment with others online, hoping to help others. As she shares her experience, she stresses that everyone is different, but that it's important to feel better -- to take your medication, to take it on time, not to scare yourself into believing that you're going to be okay.

"I hope my country, my city, will be as well as I am, " she said on Weibo on the day she was released from the hospital

Here's what she said:

I work in medical equipment and live in Huangshi. I've been thinking about my experience ever since I came home from this infection. Many netizens to ask me the specific treatment process, with what drugs, and so on, I share with you a lot of content, but also shot a video for you to see, the state of recovery is still pretty good.

Back on January 27th, I took my temperature and it was 102. Before this, cough for several days, dry cough, but the mental state and appetite is OK.

At that time, if I had not seen the news of the outbreak, I might have been quite strong, because I myself was not serious and had no special physical reaction. Later, I still felt it was necessary to go to the hospital for examination and confirmation, because my husband returned from Wuhan on the night of January 22, although so far he has shown no signs of infection.

That day, I decided to drive to the second hospital in Huangshi by myself. I didn't do much preparation before I went there. My family thought I would be OK. Results to the hospital after examination, the doctor told me two lung infection, asked the basic situation, and then recommended isolation in hospital observation. I've been here for over 10 days.

The waiting to be diagnosed is the hardest part. On January 28th, I was admitted to a solitary confinement ward. The first time I was in the hospital, I "enjoyed" the single room, I can only wry smile, in fact, that night I began to anxiety, my daughter is only four and a half years old, if really diagnosed, I am very worried about their infection to her, and miss her very much.

The first two days in the hospital there has been no treatment, feeling more and more serious cough. It wasn't until January 29th, the third day of Hospitalization, that the nurses came in armed and ready to take my blood.

At that time looked at a cell phone, the husband sent a message, said he and his daughter are awake, let me go back to sleep, then dad called to say to give me something, I refused. Old people are susceptible, and I really don't want him to come to the hospital.

That morning, people from the community and the CDC kept calling me, asking about the outbreak and exposure history. Wait till noon, then the nurse will come and inform you that you will be transferred to another hospital. I asked her if she had a diagnosis, and she said she had to wait for the doctor to call. In that case, I was anxious to know the outcome. It was not until after 2 pm that the doctor informed me that I was infected and was transferred to Huangshi Hospital of Traditional Chinese Medicine (City Hospital of Infectious Diseases) .

We took a group of seven patients with mild illness, together by ambulance to the Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine. I remember the atmosphere at the time was that everyone was a little anxious, three of them were a family, and they kept saying how much they regretted going to new year's and maybe hurting others as well.

When I got to the hospital and really settled down, I was in a better frame of mind because I had accepted it. My husband didn't believe it at first, and it was a little overwhelming, but when I did go to the hospital, he started encouraging me, saying, "I'm sure you'll be fine. "

My husband and I have been together for 11 years, married for five or six years, the relationship has actually been attributed to insipid. When I got out, he told me that he was really worried and didn't know what was going on. For the first time, he said, I was more important to him than anything.

I thought about sending out a message about the infection, but decided not to hide it. During that time, I kept tweeting because I was anxious and didn't want to talk about it in my friends'circle. Weibo was a small window. After being noticed by netizens, many people were concerned about me, and I was the first to post the diagnosis on Weibo. For the next few hours, I was exchanging information on the Internet. Many people encouraged me to be strong and cheer me on. Finally, I was touched by 100 encouraging comments.

I skyped with my daughter every day while I was in the hospital, and at first she would ask where my mother had gone. She is only four and a half years old, do not know "virus" is what, after coming home from the hospital to tell her this, she is still a very confused look, just asked why can not go to school. My mom doesn't live with us. She's the most nervous. In my days in hospital, in order not to affect my rest and treatment, she did not dare to call me, but every day even made more than a dozen phone calls to my home to ask about my situation.

I take medicine on time every day according to the doctor, eat on time, drink more water, basically did not think anything else, because many people than I am serious, I think I should not be what. One of the other patients in the same ward came in with the most severe illness, with a fever as high as 40 degrees, but was treated by the doctors and discharged before me. So I said on Weibo, don't feel the fever is more serious, this is a process, you just need to take your medicine, on time, don't scare yourself, believe that they will be fine.

Our Ward is full of patients with mild illness, mutual encouragement more, because are young people, most of the time is their own rest, at meal time will discuss which food is the best to eat, to persuade picky patients eat more. The girl next to him is facetiming with her husband every few hours, and people make jokes.

However, on the morning of February 4, a patient went to the ICU, and the doctor said in the wechat group that he needed to explain his condition to his family and prepare himself mentally. In all the time I've been in the hospital, this is the first time I've heard of a patient dying, and it's like, you never know which comes first, tomorrow or the accident.

In fact, really become a patient, just know how hard the medical staff, and see the kind of moving news is not the same. Patients can still rest in bed every day, but doctors and nurses can not rest, every day to accompany us, but also to injection, medicine, hair rice. What impressed me most was the time a doctor came in with a limp and had to comfort a patient. When I asked him what was wrong, he told me that his leg was too painful.

At the beginning of my stay in the hospital, I refresh the news every day. Before I was diagnosed, I contacted my classmates and found 100 masks to donate to Wuhan Red Cross. I spent a lot of time in Wuhan when I was a student, and I had feelings for the city. I felt heavy when I saw the news of the epidemic, so I basically stopped reading it and tried to relax by watching something else.

On February 6th, the doctor ordered a nucleic acid test. The first test was negative. Number seven ran a second test, both of which came back negative. On the morning of the 8th, after the CT scan, the doctor informed me that I was ready to leave the hospital.

We can finally go home. The girl who was transferred with me was very happy for me, but she was very nervous to see that I could be discharged, because her symptoms were also very mild and she was tested twice. The first time it was negative, the second time it was positive, and the doctor said she needed to continue treatment. We did not add wechat, after discharge from the hospital I also quit the ward group, I hope she is also discharged now.

When I got out of the hospital, my mother called me immediately, and she immediately started crying, saying she had never been so worried or upset. I posted my own discharge on Weibo, where I wrote, I really hope my country and my city will be as well as I am.

Why am I the only one in the family who's infected? Later, we carefully recalled that after my husband drove back from Wuhan, we had gone to the supermarket to buy something with my daughter. All three of us wore masks, but halfway through, I had a problem with my mask, so I took it off for a while, and he hasn't left the House since. So, did I catch it in the supermarket? I don't know yet. It's just a guess.

There is one thing worth mentioning. Home after the people have property to seal the door, my husband and they had some disputes, the family mood is already very anxious, property attitude is very hard, do not knock on the door, speak very bossy.

The main thing is, we weren't notified before the doors were sealed. My family hasn't been out of the hospital since I was diagnosed. On February 10th, my husband went out to buy food and then closed the door. We didn't prepare in advance, so it was a bit overwhelming.

After the first dispute, the second property of two or three o'clock in the middle of the night to seal the door secretly. We spoke to the community, and the staff was kind enough. On the morning of February 12th, someone from the public security bureau knocked on the door and told us to seal it. The whole process was quite gentle and handled well, and we were willing to cooperate.

I think both sides need to understand each other, but it is better to send some community personnel who are more skilled in grass-roots work to do the work of closing the door, to avoid disputes. It's just a personal suggestion, but when my isolation is over, I'd like to volunteer and do my part.

I have seen a young man from Guangdong on Douyin who voluntarily donated plasma after he was discharged from hospital. If necessary, I would also like to donate plasma containing antibodies to help the sick patients. I really hope that the epidemic will be over soon, that everyone will be safe, that all the medical staff and the grassroots workers will be able to go home safely.

Both my husband and I feel very lucky after this illness. For me, the biggest change is the realization that health comes first. I used to stay up all night and read good books no matter how late I stayed up. But now is to force themselves to go to bed early, can not sleep on lying down, be sure to adjust the schedule well.

My husband says he used to be so busy with work that he now feels that nothing is more important than having his family around. His hometown is in the northeast, this year could not go back, in-laws have been actually worried about us. When the epidemic is over, the first thing I want to do is to take my daughter and husband back to see the two old people.

At the request of the interviewee, Lin Qi was given an alias
